    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-02-08T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-02-08T08:00:00-05:00" n="257"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d257">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00115 European War 1939/261: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-02-08T13:00:00+00:00"
                            >February 8, 1940—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 8—8:48 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>335. My 331, February 7, 7 p.m., and Berlin’s 46, February 2, 9 a.m., to
                        London.<note n="3a" xml:id="d257fn3a">For the latter, see telegram of
                        February 2, 10 p.m., from the Chargé in the United Kingdom, <ref
                            target="#pg_187">p. 187</ref>.</note> It appears that the proposals
                    contained in the Department’s telegram 1107, September 29, 5 p.m.,<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d257fn4">
                        <ref target="frus1939v01#pg_641">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1939, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 641</ref>.</note> concerning the
                    treatment of civilian enemy aliens are now being given practical effect by the
                    British and German Governments except as concerned able-bodied men of military
                    age. I am orally advised by a competent official of the Foreign Office that a
                    further note accepting the proposals for the release of such men made in the
                    Department’s telegram and in the German memorandum of October 14 (Berlin’s 1727,
                    October 16, 5 p.m.)<note n="5" xml:id="d257fn5">See telegram No. 1272, October
                        19, 1939, 2 p.m., to the Ambassador in France, <ref
                            target="frus1939v01#pg_642">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 642</ref>.</note> is in course of
                    preparation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
